\begin_layout Section*
Question 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An expectation of a future temporary shock to the output 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{t+2}>0\Rightarrow Y_{t+2}=Y(1+a_{t+2})>Y_{t}$
\end_inset

) leads to an increase in the discounted present value of the total output,
 which in turn leads to an increase in the consumption 
\series bold
today
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the consumption increases, there is more demand to funds (people tend
 to consume more at the present, rather than save for later).
 thus the interest rate today (
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

) 
\series bold
rises
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Euler equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+r_{t+1}=(1+\rho)\frac{(1+z_{t+1})(1+a_{t+2})}{(1+a_{t+1})(1+z_{t+2})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+r_{t}=(1+\rho)\frac{(1+z_{t})(1+a_{t+1})}{(1+a_{t})(1+z_{t+1})}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking into account that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{t}=a_{1+t}=0<a_{t+2}$
\end_inset

 we can conclude:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{t}<r_{t+1}=r_{t+2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

